    <title>Combined summary - A compromise between BIP101 and Pieter's proposal</title>
    <updated>2023-06-10T17:58:50.690638+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://lists.linuxfoundation.org/pipermail/bitcoin-dev/2015-August/009854.html" rel="alternate"/>
    <summary>The context revolves around the issues related to Bitcoin, such as decentralization, security, and block size limit increase. The community discusses proposed changes to the block size and deployment period, with some proposing a compromise between BIP101 and BIP103. The proposed solution suggests a gradual increase in the block size over time, starting with an increase every 97 days until exactly 8MB is reached on May 11, 2017. There is disagreement among the community regarding the starting date for the block size increase, which is set to be 30 days after 75% miner support but not before January 12, 2016.Adam Back highlights concerns regarding the trustworthiness of data-center operators and suggests reading books to understand the importance of decentralization. The email thread further discusses Pieter Wuille's proposal for a block size limit increase and a compromise between Gavin's BIP101 and Pieter's proposal called "BIP103." Additionally, the argument has been made that running Bitcoin in an offshore VPS could be much easier if living in a country with repressive government.The author suggests that trusting data centers to run verified code without being hacked or responsive to court orders is delusional, and highlights the reality of policy attack and centralization points for policy attack. To ensure decentralization and avoid geopolitical risks, the author suggests establishing multiple full nodes all over the world, including in offshore VPS. The email thread discusses Pieter Wuille's proposal for a block size limit increase in Bitcoin, with details on initiation, starting date, and gradual increase in block size over a period of 16 months. The proposal aims to create an uncontroversial expectation of growth with technology, with the growth rate based on global bandwidth accessibility. The context also discusses the possibility of a group of evil individuals investing in Bitcoin's demise by making a set of prepared transactions to fill a seemingly random, bloated, and useless block. The email thread also includes discussions on the issue of trust in data centers and their ability to run verified code, avoid being hacked, filter traffic, and respond to court orders without notifying users. Finally, the article discusses the challenges of running a full node for Bitcoin in countries with repressive governments and the need for decentralization to avoid geopolitical risks. Members suggest understanding the importance of decentralization through reading books like Kicking the Dragon and The State to maintain the value of cryptocurrencies like Bitcoin. There is agreement among the community on the importance of maintaining decentralization and security in Bitcoin, with concerns regarding data-center operators and the need for gradual increases in the block size limit over time.</summary>
